## 10. Risks & Mitigations

### 10.1 Technical Risks

**Risk: AI Generation Latency**
- **Impact:** User frustration if scene generation takes >5 seconds
- **Probability:** Medium (depends on API load)
- **Mitigation:**
  - Implement request timeout at 10 seconds
  - Show estimated time and progress indicator
  - Cache common generation patterns
  - Allow user to continue editing other scenes while waiting
  - Provide "Cancel" option for long requests
  - Use streaming responses if available from Claude API

**Risk: Database Query Performance**
- **Impact:** Slow load times with 20+ scenes
- **Probability:** Low (with proper indexing)
- **Mitigation:**
  - Index story_id and position fields
  - Lazy load scene content (load list first, content on demand)
  - Implement pagination for 50+ scenes
  - Use Supabase real-time efficiently
  - Monitor query performance with logging

**Risk: Auto-save Conflicts**
- **Impact:** Data loss or overwrites in multi-device scenarios
- **Probability:** Low (single user, but possible)
- **Mitigation:**
  - Implement optimistic locking with version numbers
  - Show conflict resolution UI if detected
  - Use Supabase real-time to detect concurrent edits
  - "Last write wins" with user notification
  - Offer to save conflicting version separately

### 10.2 User Experience Risks

**Risk: Framework Too Complex**
- **Impact:** Users abandon scene tool due to perceived difficulty
- **Probability:** Medium (three sections may feel overwhelming)
- **Mitigation:**
  - Progressive disclosure: start with ACTION only, unlock others
  - Clear "Movie Time Explained" tutorial on first use
  - Allow skipping optional fields
  - Templates reduce cognitive load
  - Quick Mode simplifies to essential fields only
  - Show completion percentage to encourage progress

**Risk: AI Generates Poor Quality Scenes**
- **Impact:** Loss of trust in AI features, manual writing only
- **Probability:** Medium (depends on prompt quality and user input)
- **Mitigation:**
  - Extensive prompt engineering and testing
  - Clear expectation setting: "AI provides drafts, you refine"
  - Easy regeneration with different parameters
  - "Edit AI Draft" as primary CTA, not "Accept"
  - Collect feedback on AI quality
  - A/B test different generation prompts
  - Show Don't Tell Coach helps improve even AI drafts

**Risk: Show Don't Tell Coach Feels Pedantic**
- **Impact:** Users ignore coach, feature unused
- **Probability:** Medium (depends on feedback tone)
- **Mitigation:**
  - Friendly, encouraging tone in feedback
  - Focus on top 3 improvements, not exhaustive list
  - Make suggestions optional, not mandatory
  - Show score improvement over time (gamification)
  - Allow dismissing coach entirely if desired
  - Test feedback language with beta users

### 10.3 Business Risks

**Risk: Low Feature Adoption**
- **Impact:** Development effort doesn't translate to usage
- **Probability:** Low-Medium (if not well-integrated)
- **Mitigation:**
  - Make scene development optional but recommended
  - Integrate tightly with story structure (auto-suggest scenes)
  - Show value early: template library immediately useful
  - Onboarding specifically highlights this feature
  - Success stories from beta users
  - Track drop-off points and optimize

**Risk: Over-reliance on AI**
- **Impact:** Users expect AI to write entire story, disappointed
- **Probability:** Medium (common misconception)
- **Mitigation:**
  - Clear messaging: AI assists, doesn't replace creativity
  - Limit AI generation to scene-level, not full story
  - Require user input before generation
  - Educational content about writing craft
  - Show Don't Tell Coach teaches, doesn't just fix
  - Celebrate user edits and customization

**Risk: Feature Scope Creep**
- **Impact:** Development timeline extends, delays MVP
- **Probability:** High (many possible enhancements)
- **Mitigation:**
  - Strict adherence to FReD scope for v1.0
  - Park "nice to have" features for v2.0
  - Focus on core Movie Time framework first
  - Templates can start with 5, expand to 10 later
  - Show Don't Tell Coach can be basic initially
  - Ruthlessly prioritize must-haves

### 10.4 Content Risks

**Risk: Inappropriate AI-Generated Content**
- **Impact:** Offensive or harmful scene content generated
- **Probability:** Low (Claude API has safety measures)
- **Mitigation:**
  - Content filtering on AI outputs
  - User reporting mechanism
  - Clear content policy
  - Manual review of flagged content
  - Age-appropriate filtering based on story type
  - Opt-out of AI features available

**Risk: Copyright/Plagiarism in AI Output**
- **Impact:** AI inadvertently reproduces copyrighted material
- **Probability:** Very Low (Claude designed to avoid this)
- **Mitigation:**
  - Include disclaimer about AI-generated content
  - Encourage users to review and edit all AI outputs
  - Plagiarism checker integration (future)
  - Clear terms of service about content ownership
  - User owns all final output

---

## 11. Open Questions

### 11.1 Design Decisions Needed

**Scene Limits:**
- â“ Should we limit maximum scenes per story?
  - Option A: No limit (allow epic novels)
  - Option B: Soft limit at 50 scenes (warning, not blocking)
  - Option C: Hard limit at 100 scenes (performance concern)
  - **Recommendation:** Soft limit at 50 with warning

**Template Customization:**
- â“ Should users be able to create/save their own templates?
  - v1.0: No (use pre-built 10 only)
  - v2.0: Yes (custom template library)
  - **Recommendation:** v2.0 feature, parking for now

**AI Draft Versioning:**
- â“ How many AI draft versions to keep?
  - Option A: Last 3 versions
  - Option B: Last 5 versions
  - Option C: All versions (storage concern)
  - **Recommendation:** Last 3 versions (balance utility and storage)

**Show Don't Tell Scoring:**
- â“ Should score be absolute or relative to user's skill level?
  - Option A: Absolute (same standards for everyone)
  - Option B: Relative (adjusted based on user history)
  - Option C: User selectable (beginner/intermediate/advanced mode)
  - **Recommendation:** Start absolute, add relative in v2.0

### 11.2 Integration Questions

**Visual Story Map:**
- â“ When user creates scene from story map, which fields auto-populate?
  - Structure beat definitely
  - Scene position definitely
  - Character involvement? (if map shows character track)
  - **Needs:** Story Map FReD completion to answer

**Export Format:**
- â“ How should scenes appear in exported story?
  - Option A: Continuous prose (scenes flow together)
  - Option B: Chapter breaks at scene boundaries
  - Option C: User choice per export
  - **Recommendation:** User choice, default to continuous

**Moral Conflict Integration:**
- â“ Should EMOTION section show moral stakes if moral framework used?
  - Yes, helpful context for writers
  - But don't force moral framework on every scene
  - **Recommendation:** Optional enhancement when moral conflict selected

### 11.3 AI Configuration Questions

**Generation Style:**
- â“ Should AI generation style vary by story type?
  - Business pitch: Concise, punchy
  - Novel: Descriptive, literary
  - Screenplay: Visual, dialogue-heavy
  - **Recommendation:** Yes, tailor prompts to story type

**Regeneration Parameters:**
- â“ What should user be able to adjust on regeneration?
  - Tone (more serious/lighthearted)
  - Length (shorter/longer)
  - Style (more/less descriptive)
  - POV (first/third person)
  - **Recommendation:** Tone and Length for v1.0

**Coach Sensitivity:**
- â“ Should Show Don't Tell Coach have difficulty settings?
  - Gentle (beginner-friendly)
  - Balanced (default)
  - Rigorous (advanced writers)
  - **Recommendation:** Balanced default, add settings in v2.0

### 11.4 Performance Questions

**Real-time Collaboration:**
- â“ Should multiple users be able to edit same scene simultaneously?
  - v1.0: No (single user app)
  - Future: Yes (collaborative writing feature)
  - **Recommendation:** Park for future, focus single user

**Offline Capability:**
- â“ How much functionality should work offline?
  - Scene editing: Yes
  - Auto-save queue: Yes
  - AI generation: No (requires API)
  - Scene list: Yes (cached)
  - **Recommendation:** Core editing offline, AI features online only

**Mobile Experience:**
- â“ Should mobile have full feature parity or simplified version?
  - Option A: Full parity (responsive design)
  - Option B: Simplified (hide advanced features)
  - Option C: View-only (edit on desktop)
  - **Recommendation:** Option B - simplified but functional

